    <div class="case-header">
      <div class="case-client">Ministry of Justice · National Probation Service</div>
      <h1 class="case-h1">Reimagining the probation service <em>experience</em></h1>

      <div class="case-meta-row">
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Duration</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">24 months</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">My Role</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">Head of Service Design</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Scope</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">National — England & Wales</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">People affected</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">250,000 per year</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="highlight-band">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">The systemic challenge</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">Probation had been partially privatised, then renationalised — leaving fractured systems, inconsistent practice, and no coherent view of the service.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">Design at stake</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">The quality of this service directly shapes reoffending rates, lives rebuilt — or not — and long-term public safety.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">My contribution</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">Led a design practice of 18 across 6 workstreams, from discovery through to beta, setting design direction and assuring delivery.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="case-body">
      <aside class="case-sidebar">
        <ul class="sidebar-nav">
          <li><a href="#c1-context">Context</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c1-approach">Approach</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c1-challenge">The hard problems</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c1-outcomes">Outcomes</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c1-reflection">Reflection</a></li>
        </ul>
      </aside>

      <div class="case-content">

        <div class="case-section" id="c1-context">
          <div class="case-section-label">Context</div>
          <h2>A service fractured by reform</h2>
          <p>In 2021, following the collapse of the Transforming Rehabilitation programme, the National Probation Service was brought back under public management. The reunification inherited a deeply fragmented estate: inconsistent case management practices, six separate digital systems with no interoperability, and a staff body that had experienced years of organisational upheaval.</p>
          <p>People on licence — among the most vulnerable adults in the justice system — encountered a service that was difficult to navigate, inconsistent by geography, and with no coherent support model for the transition from custody into the community.</p>
          <p><strong>This was not primarily a digital problem.</strong> It was a service design problem — about how relationships are structured, how staff time is spent, how information flows, and how trust is built with people at the most difficult point in their lives.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c1-approach">
          <div class="case-section-label">Approach</div>
          <h2>Building the picture before designing the solution</h2>

          <p>My first task was to resist the pull toward premature solutioning. The programme had inherited political pressure to "fix the digital tools" — but no shared understanding of what good looked like for either staff or people on probation. I made the case for a structured discovery phase before any design activity.</p>

          <div class="pullquote">
            <p>"The digital tools are a symptom. The system is the problem. We have to understand the system before we can change anything in it with confidence."</p>
            <cite>— From my brief to programme leadership, January 2022</cite>
          </div>

          <p>I structured discovery across four parallel research workstreams: the lived experience of people on licence, the working reality of probation practitioners, the institutional constraints facing senior leaders, and the systemic patterns that created poor outcomes. Research ran simultaneously across 12 probation regions over 14 weeks.</p>

          <div class="process-steps">
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">01</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Shadowing and ethnographic research</h4>
                <p>Embedded researchers with probation practitioners across custody, court, and community settings to capture the lived texture of the job — not just process flows, but the decisions, workarounds, and informal knowledge that make the service function.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">02</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Co-design with people on licence</h4>
                <p>Facilitated participatory design sessions with people under active supervision — an approach that required sustained ethical scaffolding and partnership with lived experience organisations. These sessions fundamentally shifted the programme's assumptions about what "good" meant.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">03</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Systems mapping and gap analysis</h4>
                <p>Built a service map across the full probation journey — 24 distinct stages from court sentence through licence completion — identifying where the system consistently failed and why. This became the foundational artefact for design prioritisation.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">04</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Institutional alignment</h4>
                <p>Ran a series of structured workshops with senior SROs and policy leads to establish shared design principles and decision-making frameworks — creating the conditions for design to be actioned, not just produced.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c1-challenge">
          <div class="case-section-label">The hard problems</div>
          <h2>Where design met institutional resistance</h2>
          <p>The most significant design challenge was not about interfaces or journeys — it was about <strong>trust and power</strong>. People on probation had consistently poor experiences of being processed, managed, and risk-assessed without any genuine engagement with their own goals, capabilities, or circumstances.</p>
          <p>Redesigning the initial appointment model — the first point of contact between someone released from custody and their Probation Practitioner — required challenging deeply embedded practice norms and risk-averse institutional culture. We ran 16 co-design workshops with frontline staff and piloted a new appointment framework in three regions, iterating against real outcomes data before recommending national rollout.</p>
          <p>I also led the design governance structure across the programme, establishing a Design Assurance Board and a set of service standards that all six workstreams were assessed against before proceeding to alpha. This was the first time a MoJ programme of this scale had applied a design quality gate systematically across a multi-supplier environment.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c1-outcomes">
          <div class="case-section-label">Outcomes</div>
          <h2>Measured against what matters</h2>
          <div class="outcome-grid">
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">34%</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Reduction in missed initial appointments in pilot regions</div>
            </div>
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">18</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Designers and researchers recruited and onboarded to the practice</div>
            </div>
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">6</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Workstreams passed design assurance into alpha phase</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>Beyond the metrics, the programme established a shared language and design practice capability within the National Probation Service that had not previously existed — laying the groundwork for sustained design-led improvement beyond the programme itself.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c1-reflection">
          <div class="case-section-label">Reflection</div>
          <h2>What I learned</h2>
          <p>The most important design decision I made on this programme was to <strong>slow down before speeding up</strong>. Political and commercial pressure to show early delivery created a constant pull toward action. Holding the space for discovery — and making the case for it with evidence — was as much a leadership act as any design decision.</p>
          <p>I also came to understand more deeply the limits of design as a discipline operating within systems designed to resist change. The best service design in the world doesn't change outcomes if the incentive structures, workforce policies, and funding models remain unchanged. Design at this level requires fluency in policy, operations, and politics — not just craft.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

