<div class="page" id="page-case2">
  <div class="container">
    <a class="case-back" onclick="showPage('home')">← Back to work</a>

    <div class="case-header">
      <div class="case-client">NHS England · Federated Data Platform Programme</div>
      <h1 class="case-h1">Connecting care: a single view of the <em>patient journey</em></h1>

      <div class="case-meta-row">
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Duration</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">22 months</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">My Role</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">Principal Service Designer</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Scope</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">14 NHS Trusts</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Context</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">Post-pandemic recovery</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="highlight-band">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">The fundamental problem</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">A patient could be seen by five different NHS organisations in one episode of care — and no single clinician had a coherent view of what had happened.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">Stakes</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">Clinical decision-making, elective recovery, and patient safety — all degraded by an inability to share the right information at the right moment.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">Design's role</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">Make a technically complex data product coherent, trustworthy, and genuinely useful to the clinicians who would depend on it.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="case-body">
      <aside class="case-sidebar">
        <ul class="sidebar-nav">
          <li><a href="#c2-context">Context</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c2-approach">Approach</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c2-challenge">Complexity</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c2-outcomes">Outcomes</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c2-reflection">Reflection</a></li>
        </ul>
      </aside>

      <div class="case-content">

        <div class="case-section" id="c2-context">
          <div class="case-section-label">Context</div>
          <h2>Fragmentation as a patient safety risk</h2>
          <p>The pandemic had exposed with brutal clarity what NHS insiders had long understood: the inability of NHS systems to share patient information across organisational boundaries was not merely an inconvenience — it was a patient safety risk of the first order. In 2021, NHS England commissioned a programme to build a federated data platform capable of surfacing a coherent view of each patient's journey across providers.</p>
          <p>I joined as Principal Service Designer at the point when the technical architecture had been chosen but no user research had been conducted. The programme was at risk of building something technically sophisticated that no clinician would trust or use.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c2-approach">
          <div class="case-section-label">Approach</div>
          <h2>Design at the intersection of data, trust, and clinical workflow</h2>

          <p>My entry point was to establish what "useful" actually meant for the clinicians who would use the platform — and this required sustained, deep engagement with clinical practice rather than assumption-led design. I established a clinical advisory panel of 28 clinicians across acute, community, and primary care settings, and structured a 12-week discovery with embedded researchers across three pilot trusts.</p>

          <div class="pullquote">
            <p>"We kept being told this would give us a 'single view' of the patient. What we actually needed was the right view, for the right decision, in the right amount of time."</p>
            <cite>— Consultant Haematologist, Sheffield Teaching Hospitals, Discovery interviews</cite>
          </div>

          <p>This insight reoriented the product design entirely. Rather than designing for a comprehensive patient record — which no clinician had the time or need to consume — I led the team to design around specific clinical decision moments: the ward round, the MDT, the discharge planning meeting, the GP handover. Each had fundamentally different information needs, urgency, and trust requirements.</p>

          <div class="process-steps">
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">01</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Clinical workflow research</h4>
                <p>Observed and documented 14 distinct clinical decision contexts across 3 trusts, creating a decision-moment framework that structured all subsequent design work.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">02</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Trust and transparency design</h4>
                <p>Ran a dedicated design sprint on data provenance — how clinicians would understand where information had come from, how recent it was, and how much to rely on it. This became a foundational design pattern across the product.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">03</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Cross-organisational service design</h4>
                <p>Mapped the information-sharing flows across 14 trusts and 3 commissioning bodies, identifying the governance, consent, and workflow dependencies that a purely technical solution would miss.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">04</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Alpha prototyping and clinical testing</h4>
                <p>Led three rounds of prototype testing with clinical teams in situ — in actual wards, actual MDTs — rather than in lab conditions. Findings radically simplified the interface design and restructured the information architecture.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c2-challenge">
          <div class="case-section-label">Complexity</div>
          <h2>When the politics are the design problem</h2>
          <p>The hardest challenge on this programme was not the design itself — it was navigating the <strong>inter-organisational trust deficit</strong> that shaped what data could be shared, and how. NHS Trusts are sovereign organisations. They had deep reservations about data governance, liability, and competitive sensitivity. These were not irrational concerns — they reflected genuine complexity in how the NHS is structured.</p>
          <p>I worked closely with legal, information governance, and clinical leadership teams across all 14 trusts to develop a consent and data-use framework that the design could be built around — rather than the design being a post-hoc interface for a governance model developed without user input. This required attending Executive committees, Board meetings, and CIO forums — operating as a design voice in rooms that had not previously included one.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c2-outcomes">
          <div class="case-section-label">Outcomes</div>
          <h2>From prototype to production</h2>
          <div class="outcome-grid">
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">14</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">NHS Trusts onboarded to the live service</div>
            </div>
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">91%</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Clinician satisfaction with information quality in user testing</div>
            </div>
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">3</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Reusable design patterns adopted across other NHS digital programmes</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>The programme passed GDS spend control assessment with no conditions — the first NHS cross-provider data programme to do so. The design patterns developed, particularly around data provenance and clinical decision context, were adopted as reference patterns by NHS Digital for other programmes.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c2-reflection">
          <div class="case-section-label">Reflection</div>
          <h2>What this changed in my practice</h2>
          <p>This programme deepened my understanding of what it means to design <strong>trust</strong> — not just usability. In high-stakes clinical environments, a product that is easy to use but whose information cannot be relied upon is worse than no product at all. Design quality here was inseparable from governance quality, data quality, and organisational relationship quality.</p>
          <p>It also reinforced my conviction that the most important moments in a design programme often happen outside the design studio — in governance meetings, procurement negotiations, and leadership conversations where the conditions for design to succeed are either created or foreclosed.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

