<div class="page" id="page-case3">
  <div class="container">
    <a class="case-back" onclick="showPage('home')">← Back to work</a>

    <div class="case-header">
      <div class="case-client">HMRC · Making Tax Digital Programme</div>
      <h1 class="case-h1">A tax service 10 million people could <em>actually use</em></h1>

      <div class="case-meta-row">
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Duration</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">3 years</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">My Role</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">Principal Service Designer</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Users</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">10M+ Self-assessment taxpayers</div>
        </div>
        <div class="case-meta-item">
          <div class="case-meta-label">Programme</div>
          <div class="case-meta-value">Making Tax Digital</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="highlight-band">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">The scale</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">Making Tax Digital was the most ambitious transformation in HMRC's history — moving 10 million taxpayers to a fully digital submission process.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">The design problem</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">Tax is complex, stressful, and consequential. The service had to reduce complexity without hiding it — and work for people with no financial confidence.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="highlight-item">
        <div class="highlight-label">My scope</div>
        <div class="highlight-text">Design leadership across the entire self-assessment journey — from registration through to submission and payment, plus agent services for 30,000 accountants.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="case-body">
      <aside class="case-sidebar">
        <ul class="sidebar-nav">
          <li><a href="#c3-context">Context</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c3-approach">Approach</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c3-challenge">The hard problems</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c3-outcomes">Outcomes</a></li>
          <li><a href="#c3-reflection">Reflection</a></li>
        </ul>
      </aside>

      <div class="case-content">

        <div class="case-section" id="c3-context">
          <div class="case-section-label">Context</div>
          <h2>Complexity at population scale</h2>
          <p>Self-assessment tax is among the most cognitively demanding interactions most citizens have with government. The existing paper and legacy digital system generated 14 million calls to HMRC contact centres annually — the majority from people who understood neither what was being asked of them nor why. Error rates drove billions in under-collection and over-payment of tax.</p>
          <p>Making Tax Digital was conceived as a fundamental redesign: moving self-assessment to a quarterly, digital-first model with real-time calculations. It was politically high-profile, technically complex, and operationally risky. The design challenge was to make a genuinely complicated legal process legible and navigable for people with no financial expertise — including those who were digitally excluded, had accessibility needs, or operated through agents.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c3-approach">
          <div class="case-section-label">Approach</div>
          <h2>Designing for the full population, not the average user</h2>

          <p>My first intervention was to challenge the programme's user model. The design had been developed with a notional "capable, digitally confident taxpayer" in mind — but self-assessment users included people with literacy challenges, those in financial crisis, rural users with poor connectivity, elderly taxpayers, and those with complex multi-income situations. <strong>Designing for the edges would make the service better for everyone.</strong></p>

          <div class="pullquote">
            <p>"I just want to know what I owe and why. Everything else is noise."</p>
            <cite>— Self-employed plasterer, London, Usability testing round 4</cite>
          </div>

          <p>I restructured the research programme to ensure representative coverage across 14 distinct user segments — from sole traders to property landlords, from graduates to pensioners. This evidence base became the basis for a significant redesign of the information architecture: prioritising the user's tax position and next action above all else, and progressively revealing complexity only when it was relevant.</p>

          <div class="process-steps">
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">01</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Population-level research</h4>
                <p>Commissioned and led a quantitative study of 3,000 self-assessment filers to establish a statistically robust user segmentation model — replacing assumption-led personas with evidence-based user groups. This structured prioritisation decisions for the next two years of design activity.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">02</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Tax logic to plain language</h4>
                <p>Led an intensive content design sprint to translate 400 pages of tax legislation and guidance into plain-language explanations and in-context help. Worked directly with HMRC legal and policy teams — establishing a design-policy collaboration model that became a reference for other HMRC programmes.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">03</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Agent services design</h4>
                <p>Led the design of the agent-facing side of the platform — used by 30,000 accountancy firms to manage their clients' tax affairs. Required a fundamentally different interaction model, trust framework, and information architecture to the taxpayer-facing service.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
              <span class="step-num">04</span>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h4>Accessibility and assisted digital</h4>
                <p>Embedded accessibility into the design process from the start — not as a post-hoc audit. Established a standing accessibility panel with disabled users across 6 access need categories, running alongside every design sprint.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c3-challenge">
          <div class="case-section-label">The hard problems</div>
          <h2>When policy and design are in conflict</h2>
          <p>The most difficult design decision on this programme was about quarterly submissions. The policy position was that taxpayers would submit income and expense information four times a year — a significant behaviour change with no historical precedent. User research was unambiguous: this would create sustained anxiety and confusion for the majority of users, and the benefit to HMRC (real-time tax data) was not legible to users as a benefit to them.</p>
          <p>I wrote a design position paper challenging the quarterly model on the basis of user evidence, and presented it to the HMRC Executive Committee and to the relevant Treasury policy team. The outcome was a negotiated compromise — an end-of-year summary submission retained as the legal moment of record, with in-year submissions as a voluntary, benefit-explained option for users who wanted it. This was a significant design-into-policy influence at the highest level.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c3-outcomes">
          <div class="case-section-label">Outcomes</div>
          <h2>Impact at national scale</h2>
          <div class="outcome-grid">
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">62%</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Reduction in self-assessment-related contact centre calls in pilot</div>
            </div>
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">10M+</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Users migrated to the digital service in first year</div>
            </div>
            <div class="outcome-cell">
              <div class="outcome-num">4.4/5</div>
              <div class="outcome-label">Average user satisfaction rating, post-launch survey</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>The service passed its GDS assessment at alpha, beta, and live phases with commendation — one of only a handful of HMRC services to do so without conditions at any stage. The content design work was adopted as a model for HMRC's wider content standards.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="case-section" id="c3-reflection">
          <div class="case-section-label">Reflection</div>
          <h2>On scale, influence, and the patience required</h2>
          <p>Making Tax Digital taught me that <strong>design influence at scale is measured in years, not sprints</strong>. The decision to challenge the quarterly submission model was not immediately welcomed — it required sustained evidence-building, strategic relationship management, and a willingness to hold a position under pressure from senior stakeholders.</p>
          <p>I also came to understand the profound responsibility that comes with designing at population scale. When a service is used by 10 million people, small friction points become massive societal costs. Every design decision is a policy decision, whether it is treated as one or not.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

